  <discussion>Sporophytes are common in Sphagnum trinitense, which can often be distinguished from
        S. cuspidatum in the field by the appearance of its branches when wet. In this state the
        branches of S. trinitense just below the capitulum resemble a fine paintbrush drawn out to a
        pointed tip. See also discussion under 29. S. fitzgeraldii and 39. S. mississippiense. Spore
        features are taken from H. A. Crum (1984).</discussion>
